Endophytic fungi are eukaryotic organisms, which exist in healthy plant tissues at certain stages of their lifecycles without causing any noticeable symptoms or harm to the host (

). The symbiotic relationship between endophytic fungi and plants provides a powerful ability to generate biologically active substances (

), such as antibacterial (

; 

), antimalarial (

), antifungal (

), anti-inflammatory, and anticancer agents (

; 

).


Irpex lacteus
(Fr.) Fr. (Phanerochaetaceae)

, a basidiomycete that biodegrades and turns dead wood white (i.e., white rot), is often used as a traditional Chinese medicine for the treatment of chronic glomerulonephritis (

). In recent years, several undescribed furan derivatives (i.e., irpexins A-H) (

), sesquiterpenoids (i. e., tremutins A-H (

), irlactins A-K (

, 

, 2019), and irpexolactins A-N (

)), triterpenes (i. e., irpeksolactins A-J) (

), and polyketides (i.e., irpexins I-J) (

) have been isolated from their metabolite compositions, and their bioactivities were explored.

The 1D NMR data ( Table 1 ) also revealed the presence of two methylenes [ δ H 2.19 (m, H-18 β ), 2.50 (m, H-18 α ), and 2.35 (m, H-19); δ C 26.0 (C-18), 30.2 (C-19)], one methine [ δ H 4.32 (dd, J = 9.1, 4.1 Hz, H-17); δ C 57.2 (C-17)], and two carboxyl units [ δ C 174.1 (C-16), 181.0 (C-20)]. These data indicated the presence of a fragment structure of pyroglutamate, through further NMR data analysis of C 5 moiety identified it as 2( S )-pyroglutamate. These results are in accordance with previous 1 H and 13 C NMR data (
;
), as well as the theoretical and experimental ECD curves for S in compound H1-1 (Fig. S104), which was also isolated in this study. Therefore, compound 9 was biosynthesized by the esterification of 5 and H1- 1 in
I. lacteus
(Fig. S105), and its theoretical ECD curve for 1 S ,6 R ,7 R ,9 S ,17 S was in good agreement with the experimental curve ( Fig. 6 ). The absolute configuration of 9 was determined to be 1 S ,6 R ,7 R ,9 S ,17 S .

Irpexolaceus G ( 17 ) was isolated as a yellowish oil, with a molecular formula of C 15 H 20 O 5 , and six degrees of unsaturation based on the HRESIMS data ( m/z 281.1379 [M+H] + , calcd for C 15 H 21 O 5 , 281.1384). The 1D NMR data of 17 were similar to ( Z )-7-deoxy-7,8-didehydro-12- hydroxysydonic acid (
), and the weak carboxyl carbon signal in the 13 C NMR spectra was confirmed by the HMBC correlations ( Fig. 5 ) from H-2 ( δ H 7.46) and H-4 ( δ H 7.48) to C-15 ( δ C 171.2) in combination with the calculation of unsaturation. The major difference was that the hydroxyl at C-12 ( δ C 63.5) in 17 was absent in ( Z )-7-deoxy-7,8-didehydro-12-hydroxysydonic acid. The double bond between C-7 ( δ C 134.6) and C-8 ( δ C 129.9) was also indicated to be Z -configuration following further analysis of the 1D NMR spectra, in accordance with previous 1 H and 13 C NMR data (
;
). The determined structure of 17 is shown in Fig. 1 .

Biogenetically, tremulane ( i ) and ( ii ) were biosynthesized based on the relative structures of compounds 1 , 2 , 5 , 9 , 12 , 13 , and 16 by cyclization and rearrangement of farnesyl pyrophosphate (FPP) ( Fig. 8 ). Tremulenolide D ( 2 ) (
), which was synthesized by a series of reactions of tremulane ( i ), may be considered a precursor of 1 , 5 , 9 , 12 , and 13 . Under the catalysis of oxidase, tremulenolide D was converted to compounds 1 , 5 , 9 , 12 , and 13 . Interestingly, the configuration of 16 differed from that of the other isolates, especially the carbon configurations of C-1 and C-7, and was possibly derived from tremulane ( ii ) obtained by cyclization of FPP ( Fig. 8 ). Lactarane skeletons ii-1 , ii-2 , and ii-3 were produced by a series of methyl migrations, as reported in the fungus
Merulius tremellosus
(
;
). Furthermore, in this study, ii-3 , the isomeride of tremulane, underwent esterification and catalytic oxidase to form compound 16 in
microbes.

